    <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
        <body>
            <div xml:id="KT373-kilavi">
                <p type="edition">alar mikkavaḻi āṟṟāḷākiya talaimakaṭkut tōḻi colliyatu. </p>


                <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Uttered by the confidante to HER, when gossip
                    increased. </p>
            </div>

            <div xml:id="KT373">
                <lg type="edition">
                    <l> nilampuṭai peyariṉu nīrtīp piṟaḻiṉu</l>
                    <l> milaṅkutiraip peruṅkaṭaṟ kellai tōṉṟiṉum</l>
                    <l> vevvāyp peṇṭir kauvai yañcik</l>
                    <l> kēṭeva ṉuṭaittō tōḻi nīṭumayirk</l>
                    <l> kaṭumpa lūkak kaṟaivira lēṟṟai</l>
                    <l> puṭaittoṭu puṭaiip pūnāṟu palavukkaṉi</l>
                    <l> kāntaḷañ ciṟukuṭik kamaḻu</l>
                    <l> mōṅkumalai nāṭaṉō ṭamaintanan toṭarpē.</l>


                </lg>

                <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                    <l>Even if the ground moved sideways, even if water became fire,</l>
                    <l>even if there appeared a border to the great sea with shining waves <note place="foot"> How to understand the dative <term xml:lang="ta">kaṭaṟku? </term> The point of the image is obviously that the sea is supposed to be endless: no other side.</note>
                </l>
                <l>– what loss [would] that [be], friend,</l>
                <l rend="indent2">fearing scandal by hot-mouthed <note place="foot">
                    <term xml:lang="ta">vevvāy </term> = "talkative" or "foul-mouthed"? </note> women,</l>
            <l rend="indent">for our attachment, established with the man from a land</l>
            <l>of high mountains,</l>
            <l rend="indent2">where the little homes [fenced] with Malabar lilies are
                        smelling</l>
            <l rend="indent2">of the ripe jackfruit from the flower-scented tree,</l>
            <l rend="indent3">after the spotty-fingered male of the sharp-toothed black</l>
            <l rend="indent3">monkeys had dug in <note place="foot">
                <term xml:lang="ta">toṭupu </term>: Cām. glosses <term xml:lang="ta"> toṇṭiyataṉāl</term> "hollow, pierced".</note> on one side [and] broken <note place="foot">
            <term xml:lang="ta">uṭaii </term>: here we find the type of absolutive connected with subject change, which signifies causality: the monkey’s action is the cause for the spreading scent of jackfruit. </note> [it]? <note place="foot">What is conveyed by the image here? A trace of fear, contrary to the superlatives? She is no longer in safety, like the fruit taken from the tree by the inconstant monkey, and the consequences of her actions betray her, as the smell betrays the fruit? </note>
    </l>


</lg>
</div>
